  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "I start talking to people with confidence but then I suddenly start fumbling mid way and become nervous,tumble upon words. How do I tackle this?",
  "response": "It's completely normal to feel nervous when talking to others, especially if the conversation is important to you. Here are some strategies to help you maintain your confidence and improve your speech flow:\n\n1. **Practice Active Listening**: Focus on what the other person is saying instead of worrying about how you will respond. This can help reduce pressure and make your responses more natural.\n\n2. **Slow Down**: When you feel yourself starting to fumble, take a deep breath and slow down your speech. Speaking more slowly can give you time to think and reduce anxiety.\n\n3. **Pause Before Responding**: It's okay to take a moment to collect your thoughts before answering a question. A brief pause can help you avoid stumbling over your words.\n\n4. **Prepare Topics**: Before engaging in conversations, think about possible topics you might discuss. Having a few key points in mind can help you feel more prepared and confident.\n\n5. **Practice Speaking**: Try rehearsing conversations with friends or in front of a mirror. The more you practice, the more comfortable you will become in real situations.\n\n6. **Positive Self-Talk**: Replace negative thoughts with positive affirmations. Remind yourself that it's okay to make mistakes and that everyone has awkward moments.\n\n7. **Embrace Imperfection**: Accept that fumbling is a part of speaking and doesn\u2019t define your abilities. Most people are more forgiving than you think.\n\n8. **Seek Feedback**: If you feel comfortable, ask friends for constructive feedback on your communication style. They may provide insights that can help you improve.\n\n9. **Join a Speaking Group**: Consider joining groups like Toastmasters, where you can practice public speaking in a supportive environment.\n\n10. **Mindfulness and Relaxation Techniques**: Practicing mindfulness or relaxation techniques, such as deep breathing or meditation, can help manage anxiety and increase your overall calmness.\n\nConsistency and practice will help you build confidence over time. Remember, everyone has moments of nervousness, and improving your speaking skills is a gradual process.",
